13/07/2010
Former British Prime Minister Tony Blair said on Thursday (July 8th) that Kosovo's independence is a done deal and the state now faces new challenges. After talks with senior officials in Pristina, he said Kosovo should focus on the economy and improve the quality of life. President Fatmir Sejdiu awarded Blair the golden Medal of Freedom. On Friday, the former prime minister addressed parliament. 
*** 
Cypriot Foreign Minister Markos Kyprianou met with his British counterpart, William Hague, in London on Monday (July 12th). The Cyprus issue and relations between the two countries were the main topics of discussion, along with ties between Turkey and the EU, and the situation in the Middle East. 
*** 
Croatian President Ivo Josipovic arrived on Monday (July 12th) for an official visit to Macedonia. He met with President Gjorge Ivanov, Prime Minister Nikola Gruevski and Parliament Speaker Trajko Veljanoski. Josipovic also spoke with Croatian businessmen and representatives of the Croatian minority in Macedonia. 
*** 
Alternate Greek Foreign Minister Dimitris Droutsas attended a memorial in Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) on Sunday (July 11th) to mark the 15-year anniversary of the Srebrenica massacre. Droutsas, who joined Serbian President Boris Tadic, EU Council President Herman Van Rompuy, Turkish Prime Minister Tayyip Recep Erdogan, French Foreign Minister Bernard Kouchner and members of the BiH tripartite presidency, laid a wreath on behalf of the Greek government. 
*** 
Montenegrin President Filip Vujanovic and visiting Serbian counterpart Boris Tadic reaffirmed on Thursday (July 8th) their countries' commitment to the EU integration process. Tadic said that co-operation among countries in the region has been improving, but warned that there are still open issues, such as border demarcation. Vujanovic urged Belgrade and Pristina to start talks in order to achieve an agreement, saying it is important for the region. 
(Various sources -- 06/07/10-13/07/10)  
